  "slug": "cassoulet",
  "title": "Cassoulet",
  "subtitle": "The great slow-baked bean and meat dish of the French southwest.",
  "excerpt": "Haricot beans slow-cooked with duck legs, pork sausages and bacon in a herbed stock, then oven-baked under a breadcrumb crust that is broken and re-formed three times to build up a thick, savoury top. A weekend project for a cold day. Serves six.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Cassoulet of the Languedoc. The three cities of Carcassonne, Castelnaudary and Toulouse dispute the canonical recipe; this version follows the Castelnaudary tradition of slow-baking with repeated crust-breaking. Julia Child's Mastering the Art of French Cooking (1961) and Elizabeth David's French Provincial Cooking (1960) provide the principal English-language references.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Cassoulet is a weekend project, not a weeknight dinner. The beans need soaking. The duck legs need browning. The crust needs breaking and re-forming three or four times during the oven. This is Saturday cooking: slow, aromatic, methodical. The result is something the stove cannot produce, a dish where every component has exchanged flavour with every other over many hours.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "infoPanel",
        "attrs": {
          "body": "Soak the haricot beans overnight in cold water. Drain and rinse before cooking. Pre-soaked beans give a creamier result than tinned. If using tinned, reduce the initial bean cooking time to 20 minutes.",
          "type": "tip",
          "heading": "Dried beans"
        }
      },
