      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Cook the beans",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Drain the soaked {{haricot-beans}} of beans. Cover with fresh cold water and bring to the boil. Simmer for 45 minutes until almost but not completely tender. Drain and set aside.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Brown the meats",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat {{duck-fat}} of duck fat in a large casserole over medium-high heat. Season {{duck-legs}} duck legs with {{sea-salt-fine}} of salt and {{black-pepper}} of pepper; brown for 4 minutes per side. Remove. Brown {{sausages-pork}} of sausages until coloured; remove. Cook {{back-bacon}} of bacon lardons for 3 minutes; remove.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Build the casserole",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "In the same pot, cook {{onion}} chopped onion and {{carrot}} diced carrot for 8 minutes over medium heat. Add {{garlic}} of sliced garlic; cook 2 minutes. Add {{tinned-tomatoes}} of tinned tomatoes, {{tomato-puree}} of tomato purée, {{stock-chicken}} of stock, {{thyme}} of thyme and {{bay-leaves}} of bay leaves. Add the beans, sausages and bacon. Nestle the duck legs on top.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Bake with crust",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the oven to 160°C. Scatter {{breadcrumbs-dried}} of breadcrumbs over the surface in an even layer. Place the casserole uncovered in the oven. After 30 minutes, break the crust with a spoon and push it into the beans. Repeat this every 30 minutes for a total of three or four times over 2 to 2.5 hours. The final crust should be thick and golden. The beans should be completely tender and the liquid reduced to a thick sauce.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Troubleshooting",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "intro": null,
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Old beans can take much longer. Add the tomatoes only after the beans are mostly tender; acid prevents them softening.",
              "cause": "Not soaked, or old dried beans, or acid in the sauce preventing softening.",
              "symptom": "Beans still hard after cooking"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Add a ladleful of warm stock or water when breaking the crust. The beans should always have some liquid covering them.",
              "cause": "Too little liquid, or oven too hot.",
              "symptom": "Casserole drying out in the oven"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Use fine dried breadcrumbs. If there is liquid pooling, break the crust and push it under; the next layer forms faster.",
              "cause": "Too much liquid at the surface, or breadcrumbs too coarse.",
              "symptom": "Crust not forming properly"
            }
          ],
          "heading": "Common problems"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The fight between Carcassonne, Castelnaudary and Toulouse over the right cassoulet recipe has run for at least a century. They argue about it like a treaty dispute. Castelnaudary claims the first version. Toulouse adds confit duck and mutton. This recipe sides with Castelnaudary's focus on the crust. Whichever town is right, cassoulet is the great winter dish of the Languedoc. Best made on a Saturday when you have nothing to do until Sunday."
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
